sentence: Home Depot is back to long-term resistance, and investors are getting nervous.
optionMONSTER's Depth Charge tracking program detected the purchase of about 7,000 February 42 puts for $0.96 to $1.04.
Volume was more than 4 times open interest in the strike.
HD rose 0.82 percent to $43.09 and is up more than 30 percent in the last three months.
Most stocks tied to housing have been strong recently, but the home-improvement retailer has also been gaining ground on rival Lowe's.
Its last two quarterly reports beat estimates, and its quarterly dividend was raised in November.
However, chart watchers may be wary as Home Depot's shares are now back near the same levels where they peaked between late 2004 and mid-2006.
That could lead some traders to expect a pullback and might explain yesterday's downside option activity.
Fourth-quarter results will be released on Feb. 21, two trading sessions after February expiration.
Overall option volume in HD was almost twice the average amount yesterday, according to the Depth Charge.
Puts outnumbered calls by almost 2 to 1.
